{"cursor":"35259","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox disease\n | Name = Typhoid fever Image = Salmonella typhi typhoid fever PHIL 2215\n | lores.jpg Caption = Rose spots on the chest of a patient with typhoid fever\n | due to the bacterium [[Salmonella]] typhi DiseasesDB = 27829 ICD10 = ICD9 =\n | ICDO = OMIM = MedlinePlus = 001332 eMedicineSubj = oph eMedicineTopic = 686\n | eMedicine_mult = MeshID = D014435\n}} 'Typhoid fever', also known simply as 'typhoid', is a common\nworldwide bacterial disease, transmitted by the ingestion of food or water\ncontaminated with the feces of an infected person, which contain the bacterium\n[[Salmonella typhi]], serotype Typhi. http://www.cd-\nc.gov/ncidod/dbmd/diseaseinfo/TyphoidFever_g.htm\n\nThe disease has received various names, such as 'gastric fever', 'abdominal\ntyphus', 'infantile remittant fever', 'slow fever', 'nervous fever' or\n'pythogenic fever'. The name \"typhoid\" means \"resembling typhus\" and comes from\nthe neuropsychiatric symptoms common to typhoid and typhus. Oxford English Dictionary. typhoid, adj. and n. and typhus, n.\nOnline version March 2011. Retrieved May 2011. Despite this similarity of\ntheir names, typhoid fever and typhus are distinct diseases and are caused by\ndifferent species of bacteria.\n\nThe impact of this disease fell sharply in the developed world with the\napplication of 20th century sanitation techniques.\n","linknr":820,"url":"Typhoid","recorded":1362501455,"links":79,"instances":["epidemiology"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Intestinal infectious diseases","Conditions diagnosed by stool test","Waterborne diseases"],"headings":["Signs and symptoms","Transmission","Diagnosis","Prevention","Medical treatment","Epidemiology","History","See also these","References","Further reading","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/Salmonella_typhi_typhoid_fever_PHIL_2215_lores.jpg/230px-Salmonella_typhi_typhoid_fever_PHIL_2215_lores.j